<p>Columnist Comments</p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p>•</p>
<p>						There's not much  Christmas cheer for our homeless</p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p>				Christmas 2011 and never mind no room at the inn - this year they've even boarded up trade union HQ to keep out the homeless.</p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p>•</p>
<p>						Old prejudices have no place in new society </p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p>Some people just can't keep out of the news. Take Belfast Lord Mayor Niall O </p>
<p>  Donnghaile. There he was, busily planning to host a reception for the brave </p>
<p>  bus drivers who kept us all on the move through the Dark Days of the </p>
<p>  Troubles.</p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p>•</p>
<p>						Anthem that divides ill at  ease with our goal of unity   </p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p>				If we want a better society, it can't be 'them' and 'us'. It can only be 'all of us'." I raise these words, spoken by the First Minister, Peter Robinson, at his party conference, in the face of two recent controversies.</p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p>•</p>
<p>						Orange, green and now amber alerts ... no wonder I’m getting alarmed </p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p>Last Wednesday, as I was driving along in the car, I heard the BBC weather man </p>
<p>  tell us that there was an ‘amber’ alert for the next day. </p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p> </p>
